	<aside class="global-south-callout reveal" aria-label="On Social Democracy and South Africa's Path">
		<h3>On Social Democracy and South Africa's Path</h3>
		<p>
			South Africa's post-apartheid governments explicitly chose neither
			the path of Nordic social democracy nor of socialist development.
			The ANC adopted GEAR in 1996 — choosing, without compulsion, the
			same fiscal orthodoxy the IMF was forcing on weaker states. The
			Freedom Charter's promises of nationalisation and redistribution
			were set aside for investor confidence and austerity politics.
		</p>
		<p>
			Social democratic states achieve genuinely better outcomes for
			their citizens than raw market capitalism — better healthcare,
			lower poverty, stronger labour rights. But the prosperity that
			makes them possible rests on a foundation that cannot be
			universalised. Western European wealth was built substantially
			on colonial extraction — including from South Africa — and is
			sustained through trade relationships that systematically
			disadvantage the Global South. A country cannot pursue the
			Nordic model when Eskom is in ruins, 32.9% of the workforce is
			unemployed, and R300 billion goes uncollected in the annual
			tax gap every year.
		</p>
		<p>
			Cuba and China demonstrate that socialist governance — even under
			decades of economic warfare from capitalist nations — can deliver
			universal healthcare, eliminate mass illiteracy, and drive
			development. Cuba, under a six-decade US blockade, developed and
			exported its own COVID-19 vaccines and deploys medical brigades
			active in 50+ countries. China eliminated extreme poverty for
			800 million people within living memory. Their adaptations are
			not failures of socialism but evidence of its resilience under
			siege. These achievements coexist with constraints on political
			and civil liberties that remain subjects of legitimate debate.
		</p>
		<p>
			South Africa has a Constitution that promises these things.
			It has a tax base large enough to fund them. What it lacks is
			the political will to confront the interests that captured
			the transition.
		</p>
		<div class="pull-quote">
			<blockquote>
				"Neocolonialism is the worst form of imperialism. For those who
				practise it, it means power without responsibility; and for those
				who suffer from it, it means exploitation without redress."
			</blockquote>
			<cite>— Kwame Nkrumah, <em>Neo-Colonialism: The Last Stage of Imperialism</em>, 1965</cite>
		</div>
